" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2362" height="1575" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-154924" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006.jpg 2362w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/16Mar_Hwange_Coal_KM006-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 2362px) 100vw, 2362px" />18 February 2022: A Hwange Colliery Company employee undertakes a magnetic mapping exercise in one of the areas in Madumabisa worst affected by coal fires.



To prevent accidents, the villagers in Hwange have been calling on mining companies to detect underground fires, erect warning signs and fence off the affected areas to keep children out.



Tomu, whose husband works at one of the local mines, says the family reported Lincoln’s injuries to the Hwange Colliery Company and asked for help with his medical bills, but to no avail. “I used a family medical aid, but I bought some of the medicines required by the doctors myself. We reported the matter to the safety manager, but all seems to have fallen on deaf ears.” 



Thobekile Shoko, a regional organiser for the National Mine Workers Union of Zimbabwe, says it’s hard to apportion blame for the fires on a single company. “Hwange as a whole is a coal mining place. Where we stay we are told the houses were built on top of the old mines and these fires just appear.” 



Shoko says awareness campaigns have been undertaken in schools, but more can be done to prevent accidents and help the victims of these fires.



